        (document.getElementsByTagName('HEAD')[0] || document.getElementsByTagName('BODY')[0]).appendChild(s);
    }());
</script></aside><h2><a href="lesson-9-consonants-part-1-and">Lesson #9: Consonants Part 1; क ka, ख kha, ग ga, घ gha and ङ ṅa  </a></h2><div class="caption clearfix rte"><p>So now you&rsquo;ve learnt all about Hindi vowels, it&rsquo;s time to crack on through the consonants, do you think you&rsquo;re ready? If you feel like you&rsquo;ve forgot anything about the Hindi vowels then head back to the to refresh yourself&nbsp;<a href="../../vowels">Vowels Section</a>!</p><p>As we saw in the <a href="../../consonants">Consonants Section</a>, Hindi consonants are nicely sorted into little groups. So are you ready to learn all about our very first group of consonants? Well here they are&hellip;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_m4umbgoK9g1qzfx8l.png"></p><p>This first group is called the Gutturals. What do you think? Do they look confusing? Well hopefully by the end of this lesson you&rsquo;ll have these five consonants mastered! So let&rsquo;s not hang around, let&rsquo;s get going with it straightaway, our first letter is&hellip;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_m4umq2qHFq1qzfx8l.png"><em>&nbsp;ka&nbsp;</em>&nbsp; &nbsp;<iframe align="middle" frameborder="no" height="70" scrolling="no" src="http://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fapi.soundcloud.com%2Ftracks%2F61707207&amp;%20%20auto_play=false&amp;show_artwork=false&amp;color=000000&amp;show_user=false&amp;%20%20show_playcount=false&amp;sharing=false&amp;show_comments=false" width="26%"></iframe></p><p><small><small>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; If you can&rsquo;t see the play button or if it wont work then&nbsp;<a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/post/17326025481/problems-with-the-audio-files">click here</a>&nbsp;for instructions on how to fix it!</small></small></p><p>This is the letter&nbsp;<big><big>&#2325;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ka</em>. What do you think it looks like? A bit like a man doing a teapot impression don&rsquo;t you think? Practice drawing it out. How do we pronounce <big><big>&#2325;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ka</em>? This is easy, it&rsquo;s just like the English k - like in words like &lsquo;kind&rsquo;, 'king&rsquo; etc. Click the play button just above to hear this letter and an example word pronounced - be sure to listen to it loads of times! Got it?&nbsp;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_m4unclN9wq1qzfx8l.png"></p><p>The Hindi word for chair is <big><big>&#2325;&#2369;&#2352;&#2360;&#2368;</big></big> <em>kursee</em>. Can you see our new consonant <big><big>&#2325;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ka</em> at the start here?&nbsp;Remember the flick underneath it is the vowel&nbsp;<big><big>&#2313;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>u</em>, as we learnt in&nbsp;<a href="../743955682/lesson-5-vowels-part-4-and">Lesson #5</a>.Listen to this word being spoken by clicking play above! Got it? Nice one! Well, that&rsquo;s one whole consonant learnt already, see that wasn&rsquo;t difficult was it? Ready for the next one? Here goes&hellip;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_m4unlzFvZs1qzfx8l.png"><em>kha</em>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<iframe align="middle" frameborder="no" height="70" scrolling="no" src="http://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fapi.soundcloud.com%2Ftracks%2F61707350&amp;%20%20auto_play=false&amp;show_artwork=false&amp;color=000000&amp;show_user=false&amp;%20%20show_playcount=false&amp;sharing=false&amp;show_comments=false" width="26%"></iframe></p><p>This is the letter&nbsp;<big><big>&#2326;&nbsp;</big></big><em>kha</em>. What does it look like? Well it&rsquo;s a funny one, I can kind of see a fat man&rsquo;s torso and he&rsquo;s wearing a tshirt with a big C on it. Be sure to practice writing it out loads!&nbsp;</p><p>So how do we pronounce <big><big>&#2326;&nbsp;</big></big><em>kha</em> then? Well this takes some explaining because it&rsquo;s probably the first letter that we&rsquo;re not used to in English. Firstly have a listen to the letter and an example word by clicking on the play button just above! So how do we make this sound? Well I want you to say the letter <big><big>&#2325;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ka</em> just as we learnt above, just like the English k. Now I want you to say it again but with your hand over your mouth like this&hellip;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_ldwgf0GS641qzfx8l.jpg"></p><p>You should feel a little breathe on your hand, try it again, say <big><big>&#2325;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ka</em>. Now to pronounce&nbsp;<big><big>&#2326;&nbsp;</big></big><em>kha&nbsp;</em>put your hand over your mouth again and make the same sound as&nbsp;<big><big>&#2325;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ka</em>,but this time push as much air from your mouth as possible, you should really feel lots of breathe on your hand. We say that&nbsp;<big><big>&#2326;&nbsp;</big></big><em>kha&nbsp;</em>is the <strong>aspirated</strong> version of&nbsp;<big><big>&#2325;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ka.&nbsp;</em></p><p>So with&nbsp;<big><big>&#2325;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>ka&nbsp;</em>you should feel a little breath and&nbsp;<big><big>&#2326;&nbsp;</big></big><em>kha&nbsp;</em>is simply the same sound, but with lots of breath. Don&rsquo;t worry if it seems really confusing to start with, just keep practicing it over and over and keep listening to the letter being pronounced and you&rsquo;ll soon get there, promise. Ready to learn the example word? &nbsp;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_m66uiiznjR1qzfx8l.png"></p><p><big><big>&#2326;&#2366;&#2344;&#2366;&nbsp;</big></big><em>khaanaa</em> is the Hindi word for food - it&rsquo;s also means &nbsp;'To Eat&rsquo;. Can you see our new letter <big><big>&#2326;&nbsp;</big></big><em>kha</em> here? Great! Make sure you listen to it plenty of times! Ready to move on to the next letter? Here goes&hellip;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_m66urzznTO1qzfx8l.png">&nbsp;&nbsp;<em>ga &nbsp; &nbsp;</em><iframe align="middle" frameborder="no" height="70" scrolling="no" src="http://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fapi.soundcloud.com%2Ftracks%2F61707474&amp;%20%20auto_play=false&amp;show_artwork=false&amp;color=000000&amp;show_user=false&amp;%20%20show_playcount=false&amp;sharing=false&amp;show_comments=false" width="26%"></iframe></p><p><br>This is the letter&nbsp;<big><big>&#2327;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ga. </em>What does it look like? It&rsquo;s a bit like a one legged man hopping around, a pirate maybe, don&rsquo;t you think? The pronounciation of this letter is easy, it&rsquo;s just like the English 'g&rsquo; from the word &ldquo;go&rdquo; or &ldquo;get&rdquo;, you can hear it pronounced by clicking the play button just above!</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_mdos77LJXO1qzfx8l.png"></p><p>We learnt the Hindi word for Fire a few lessons ago in&nbsp;<a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/post/727352299/lesson-2-vowels-part-1-a-and-aa">Lesson #2</a>. Can you remember what it was? That&rsquo;s right it&rsquo;s -&nbsp;<big><big>&#2310;&#2327;&nbsp;</big></big><em>aag</em> - Fire. Can you spot our new letter&nbsp;<big><big>&#2327;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ga </em> here? <big><big>&#2309;&#2330;&#2381;&#2331;&#2366;&nbsp;</big></big><em>acchaa</em> - Good! Don&rsquo;t forget to listen to this word by clicking play above. Ready for letter number four of this group?</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_m66v3zULLY1qzfx8l.png">&nbsp;<em>gha &nbsp; &nbsp;</em> <iframe align="middle" frameborder="no" height="70" scrolling="no" src="http://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fapi.soundcloud.com%2Ftracks%2F61707647&amp;%20%20auto_play=false&amp;show_artwork=false&amp;color=000000&amp;show_user=false&amp;%20%20show_playcount=false&amp;sharing=false&amp;show_comments=false" width="26%"></iframe></p><p>This is the letter&nbsp;<big><big>&#2328;&nbsp;</big></big><em>gha</em>. What does this letter look like? Well I think it looks like a sideways bum but don&rsquo;t tell anyone I said that!</p><p>Now just like&nbsp;<big><big>&#2325;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ka</em> and <big><big>&#2326;&nbsp;</big></big><em>kha, </em><big><big>&#2328;&nbsp;</big></big><em><em>gha&nbsp;</em></em>is the <strong>aspirated</strong> version of <big><big>&#2327;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ga. </em>So to pronounce <big><big>&#2328;&nbsp;</big></big><em>gha</em> all we do is make the sound <big><big>&#2327;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ga&nbsp;</em>with lots of breath<em>. </em>You can hear this letter being pronounced by clicking play above! Remember to put your hand over your mouth to make sure you&rsquo;re expelling lots of air when you say <big><big>&#2328;&nbsp;</big></big><em>gha</em> and as little air as possible when you say <big><big>&#2327;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ga. </em>Have you got it?</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_m66v8hWOBW1qzfx8l.gif"></p><p>Ready for an example word? The Hindi word for &ldquo;house&rdquo; or &ldquo;home&rdquo; is&nbsp;<big><big>&#2328;&#2352;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ghar -</em> be sure to listen to the word above! I&rsquo;m sure you can see the letter <big><big>&#2328;&nbsp;</big></big><em>gha</em> at the start! Phew, ok breathe in, I need your concentration for only a minute longer. Are you ready for the last letter of this group?&nbsp;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_m66vbuWkiX1qzfx8l.png">&nbsp; <em>&#7749;a &nbsp;&nbsp;</em> <iframe align="middle" frameborder="no" height="70" scrolling="no" src="http://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fapi.soundcloud.com%2Ftracks%2F61707740&amp;%20%20auto_play=false&amp;show_artwork=false&amp;color=000000&amp;show_user=false&amp;%20%20show_playcount=false&amp;sharing=false&amp;show_comments=false" width="26%"></iframe></p><p>This is the letter&nbsp;<big><big>&#2329;&nbsp;</big></big><em>&#7749;a</em>. This may seem like a bit of a cheat but all I&rsquo;m going to tell you about this letter now is that it&rsquo;s pronounced like the n in the English word 'ink&rsquo; - and guess what, you can hear it being pronounced by clicking play above! This letter is really rare so we&rsquo;ll cover it in more detail later!</p><p>Wow! So that&rsquo;s your first group of consonants done! How did you find it? Hopefully you now know five more Hindi letters! Be sure to keep practicing them to make sure you don&rsquo;t forget them. Head back to the Consonants section now and start on the next group!&nbsp;</p><p><a href="../../consonants">Click to go back to the Consonants Section</a>.&nbsp;</p></div><aside class="post-footer"><div class="tags"><span>Tags:</span><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/consonants">consonants</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/ga">ga</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/gha">gha</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/ka">ka</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/kha">kha</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/gutturals">gutturals</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/july2010">july2010</a> </div><div class="bottom"><div class="like_button" data-post-id="798066644" data-blog-name="learninghindi" id="like_button_798066644"><iframe id="like_iframe_798066644" src="http://assets.tumblr.com/assets/html/like_iframe.html?_v=5716f9145cbbcc5e21aa13229de5d4ed#name=learninghindi&amp;post_id=798066644&amp;color=grey&amp;rk=SOigltjz" scrolling="no" width="16" height="16" frameborder="0" class="like_toggle" allowTransparency="true" name="like_iframe_798066644"></iframe></div><a href="https://www.tumblr.com/reblog/798066644/SOigltjz" class="reblog_button"style="display: block;width:16px;height:16px;"><svg width="100%" height="100%" viewBox="0 0 21 21" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" fill="#ccc"><path d="M5.01